{"add":{"doc":{"id":"a9cce03c5885958326667d204346c525affe4665327e17ccfde46310519b2c4b","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Leffler_-1968_WashingtonDC_MLK_riots.jpg/220px-Leffler_-1968_WashingtonDC_MLK_riots.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Major riots in black neighborhoods caused a series of \"long hot summers.\" They started with a violent disturbance in Harlem riots in 1964, and the Watts district of Los Angeles in 1965, and extended to 1971. The momentum for the advancement of civil rights came to a sudden halt in the summer of 1965, with the riots in Watts. After 34 lives were lost, along with $35 million in property damage, the public feared an expansion of the violence to other cities, and so the appetite was lost for additional programs in LBJ's agenda.[136]"]}}}